this is one of the most misunderstood features in JavaScript.
The interesting part is that this doesn't care where a function is written. It only cares how that function is called
Once you understand this single idea, almost every this interview question becomes straightforward.

💡 What is this?
this is a special keyword that JavaScript automatically provides to every execution context.
Unlike normal variables, you never assign a value to this.
Instead, JavaScript decides its value at runtime, when the function is actually called.
function greet() {
console.log(this);
}At this point, JavaScript still doesn’t know what this is.
It waits until someone calls the function.
greet();Only then does JavaScript determine the value of this.

⭐ The One Rule You Should Remember
If you only remember one thing from this article, make it this:
this depends on how a function is called, not where it is defined.
Everything else in this article is simply an application of this rule.

🔍 Where Does this Come From ?
Every time JavaScript executes a function, it creates a brand new Execution Context.
( will talk about Execution Context in another article in detail )
An execution context contains three important things :
👉 Variable Environment
👉 Scope Chain
👉this
Unlike variables, the value of this isn't fixed beforehand. It is assigned when the function starts executing, based on how that function was invoked.
🤯 This is why the exact same function can have different values of this.
( now it may sounds intimidating but after knowing the complete scenario it will be cleared )

🌍 Scenario 1: Global Context
Outside of any function, this refers to the global object.
Browser
console.log(this);Output
WindowBecause the global object in browsers is window.

Node.js
console.log(this);Output
{}or
module.exportsdepending on the module system.

🚀 Scenario 2: Regular Function
Consider a simple function.
function greet() {
console.log(this);
}greet();Without Strict Mode
Output
windowSince no object called the function, JavaScript falls back to the global object.

With Strict Mode
"use strict";function greet() {
console.log(this);
}greet();Output
undefinedStrict mode prevents JavaScript from automatically using the global object.
This helps catch bugs much earlier.

🏠 Scenario 3: Object Method
When a function is called as a method,
object.method()the object before the dot becomes this.
const person = {
name: "John", greet() {
console.log(this.name);
}
};person.greet();Output
JohnHere,
person.greet()means that person is calling the function.
So JavaScript sets
this === person
You can verify this directly.
const person = {
greet() {
console.log(this);
}
};person.greet();Output
{
greet: ƒ
}The entire object becomes this.

🏗️ Scenario 4: Constructor Function
When a function is called with new, JavaScript creates a brand new object.

