That newly created object becomes this.
function Person(name) {
this.name = name;
}const john = new Person("John");console.log(john.name);Output
JohnInternally, JavaScript roughly performs these steps:
const obj = {};Person.call(obj, "John");return obj;So inside the constructor,
this.name = name;actually adds the property to the newly created object.

🖱️ Scenario 5: Event Listeners
Inside a regular event listener callback, this refers to the element that received the event.
button.addEventListener("click", function () {
console.log(this);
});Output
<button>Click</button>Because the button is effectively calling the callback.

🏹 Scenario 6: Arrow Functions
Arrow functions are special.
They do not create their own this.
Instead, they inherit this from the surrounding scope.
This behavior is called lexical this.
const person = {
name: "Alice", greet: () => {
console.log(this.name);
}
};person.greet();Output
undefinedMany developers expect
Alicebut that’s not what happens.
The arrow function never receives
this = personInstead, it uses the this from the place where it was created.
In a browser, that’s typically the global object.
So JavaScript is effectively reading
window.nameinstead of
person.name
💡 Why Arrow Functions Work This Way 🤔
Normal functions receive a new this every time they're called.
Arrow functions simply reuse the surrounding one.
const person = {
name: "Alice",
greet() {
const sayHi = () => {
console.log(this.name);
};
sayHi();
}
};
person.greet();Output
AliceHere’s what’s happening:
greet()↓
this = person
↓
sayHi()
↓
inherits the same this
↓
this = person
This is one of the biggest reasons arrow functions were introduced.

⚠️ Common Mistake
Many developers write this:
const person = {
name: "John",
greet() {
const sayHi = () => {
console.log(this.name);
};
sayHi();
}
};person.greet();
…and expect
JohnInstead, the output is usually
undefined✅ Correct Approach
If you need this, use a regular method.
const person = {
name: "John",
greet() {
console.log(this.name);
}
};
🧩 Interview Question
🤔 What does this code print ?
const person = {
name: "John", greet() {
console.log(this.name);
}
};
const fn = person.greet;
fn();
Answer
Nothing is calling greet() as a method any more. The function is now invoked like this:
fn();This is simply a regular function call.
In strict mode:
this === undefinedTherefore,
this.namethrows a Type Error.
The connection to person was lost when the method was assigned to another variable.

🎯 Key Takeaways

• ✅ this is assigned when a function is called, not when it's created.

• ✅ The call site determines the value of this.

• ✅ Every function execution gets its own this.

• ✅ Arrow functions don’t have their own this. They inherit it from the surrounding scope.

• ✅ When debugging, don’t look at where the function is defined. Look at how it’s invoked.

💭 A simple way to remember it:
When you’re confused about this, ignore the function definition for a moment. Find the line where the function is called. In almost every case, that line tells you exactly what this will be.
